  <text>
    <body><div type="letter">
      <p>St James' Sqre Friday. 1/2 past five</p>
      <p>Dearest W. I have got here without any undue return of the head or other symptoms; but (of course) I am feeling ill, &amp; have strange sensations.</p>
      <p>The drive, air, &amp; motion rather did good than otherwise.</p>
      <p>The Hen was very kind, &amp; drove on with me as far as Kingston. She advises (but says of course I should be</p>
      <p>guided by my Doctor) that I should remain in Town at any rate till Monday. I can decide nothing about this until tomorrow. Tho' not alarmed, she yet evidently thinks the state just now requires close watching, &amp; that I ought to have help at hand if those head attacks are likely to recur; &amp; this we probably cannot tell for a day or two.</p>
      <p>She is to come here by one tomorrow, &amp; will remain in Town, if I do. This would be a great comfort.</p>
      <p>She thinks the excitement of this correspondence (altho' she does not know that I wrote any of the letter), has had much to do with aggravating an already distressed state of brain.-- I certainly felt as if it was too much for me; &amp; the letter to Hester it has been impossible for me to go on with. My mother has begged me to banish all disagreeable &amp; anxious topics from my mind for the present; thinking that really my safety, as well as comfort, demands it.</p>
      <p>Fortunately, I really have a</p>
      <p>degree of practical philosophy now; &amp; am equally ready for life or death; as the case may turn out to be.</p>
      <p>By the bye Mrs King (who by the way, thought me looking very ill), has expressed that it was indeed a "great delight to see me" "in so undoubtedly a very" "satisfactory state of mind."</p>
      <p>I think we ought to send word of this to Woburn.</p>
      <p>My going to the Greigs is out of the question, in the state I am.--</p>
      <p>I have not yet seen Locock.--</p>
      <p>Ever The Bird</p>
    </div></body>
